\begin_layout Subsection
Short-Term CF
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lifecycle of a product/firm usually consists (roughly) of an introduction,
 growth, maturity and decline phases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is relevant, because in order to talk about a company that is 
\series bold
continually growing
\series default
 - it might be assumed that 
\series bold
new projects
\series default
 are always launched.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is an 
\series bold
upper limit
\series default
 to the growth a firm can have (market size limitation - consider for example
 Apple, Tesla, etc).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A firm cannot grow indefinitely, without innovationg new businesses and
 operations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The higher the firm value is, the more innovative it has to be.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The long-term growth rate is therefore capped, and cannot drastically differ
 from the overall industry rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Short-term
\series default
 is commonly defined as ~5 years, whereas 
\series bold
long-term
\series default
 is usually 6+ years (reaching a steady state).
 The reason that management is assumed to forecast and make plans to roughly
 5 years.
 Sometimes there are exceptions (for example: a patent is 
\series bold
not
\series default
 a steady state, its short-term is >5 years; Kellogg's in Brazil).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
yield curve
\series default
 is one of the most important aspects in valuation.
 It is usually increasing (with a decreasing slope), having main impact
 in 5-10 years.
 In most cases (70%-90% of valuations), 5 years is the appropriate cut-off,
 yet it is worth knowing when to deviate from it.
\end_layout

