First, consider the market (its size and the company share) and the whole
 industry.
 Example: Haifa port valuation.
 There are 3 ports: Haifa, Ashdod (historically 50%-50%) and a Chinese port,
 which will start operationg in the future.
 First, a demand analysis is made, to find out the total demand function.
 Then, a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

split
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 between the Northern Israel and Center is considered (the price effect
 is modeled as well - e.g cars are likely to be still shipped to Ashdod,
 unlike metal).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the first approach, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the Chinese are going to steal every bit of import, to operate their port
 at a full capacity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, then only the leftovers are in the Haifa port.
 In such case, every marginal growth goes to Haifa.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

If the situation is bad quantity-wise, it might be not so bad price-wise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative approach is to compete and lower the prices.
\end_layout

