\begin_layout Subsection
Operating profits forecasting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 3 options:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Specifically estimate cost items
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Allocate costs to fixed / variable items.
 Is the historical COGS an accurate estimate of the future? - It usually
 is, but not always.
 There are fixed & variable costs.
 Sometimes the response function is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

step-wise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The question is: how much of the cost and fixed, and how much of it is
 variable? The firm, its operations and the reasonable profitability margin
 need to be understood.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Estimate EBIDTA (% of sales)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Operating costs as a linear function of sales can be plotted (using a regression
), to determine the intercept and the plot (notice the 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

).
 In order to provide more accurate results, many data points are recommended,
 and a separate estimate for each item.
 Usually salaries are the most expensive item in SG&A, and a natural increase
 is usually assumed over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Depreciation estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usually a constant ratio of gross/net fixed assets to sales is assumed.
 This approach can be bad, as 
\series bold
gross
\series default
 assets are depreciated, thus looking at a ratio with net assets does not
 make sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usually, the NFA/sales ratio can be actually projected.
 The NFA might not depend on the sales (e.g Intel - 50% spare capacity),
 but usually that is not the case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The depreciation is a function of the 
\series bold
historical
\series default
 figures (thus there is no circular reference).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

easy route
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of not starting from the historical investment but form the NFA might lead
 to inaccurate results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tax rate forecasting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
The tax is hell
\series default
.
 If there is access to the firm, it is always better to ask the exact tax
 figures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Otherwise, a rule of thumb is taking the average (effective) tax rate.
 In case of a valuation for a specific division/project in the firm, the
 statutory tax rate is usually taken (23%-25%), assuming all tax benefits
 remain in the firm.
\end_layout

