\begin_layout Subsection
Illustration of operation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a simplified form, an activity of a firm can be described as a cycle
 of:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Investing capital to produce NOPAT.
 Recalling, invested capital consists of fixed assets, intangibles, NWC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Return on invested capital (ROIC) is the NOPAT, divided by the invested
 capital.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
From the NOPAT, some portion is paid out (payout ratio), the remaining is
 reinvested (at the reinvestment rate) back.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A study made by McKinsey shows that ROIC of firms (divided to groups by
 quantiles) tend to converge over time.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 / 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 groups do not intersect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an exmple with Tiv-Taam: it was purchased for $250M, and being
 prepared for an IPO in 2007.
 A consultancy firm valued it at $445M.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consultancy firm assummed that Tiv-Taam would grow roughly twice in
 5 years.
 The asssumption was the NOPAT would grow x5.
 Fixing the ROIC, increasing revenues requires more investment (basically,
 more fixed assets are needed).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analysis assumes the ROIC would increase from ~5% to ~21% (much higher
 than the usual profitability in the industry).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The projections were way off, by assuming either too high NOPAT or too low
 capex.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
implied ROIC 
\series default
line is very important to check.
 Many practitioners miss it, and it might reveal mistakes in the analysis.
\end_layout

